1228":"before 1228","1290":"1290","1228":"1228","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1255":"1255","1453":"1453","1200":"1200","about 1254":"about 1254","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Northampton, Northamptonshire, England":"Northampton, Northamptonshire, England","England":"England","Potter Newton, Yorkshire, England":"Potter Newton, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hansard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): of Norman origin, from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Ansard</i> with prosthetic <i>H-</i>; from ancient Germanic <i>ans-</i> ‘(pagan) god’ + <i>ward</i> ‘guard, protector’ or <i>hard-</i> ‘brave, hardy’."],"variants":[{"name":"Hazard","meanings":["English: Anglo-Norman French variant of   Hansard  .","English and French: nickname from Old French, Middle English <i>hasard</i>, <i>hazard</i> ‘game of dice’, perhaps given to a player at hazard, i.e. a gambler, trickster, or rascal. The word probably derives from Arabic <i>az-zahr</i>, from <i>az</i>, assimilated form of the definite article <i>al</i>, + <i>zahr</i> ‘die’. It appears to have been picked up in the Holy Land and brought back to Europe by Provençal crusaders.","English: possibly in some instances of Flemish origin, a nickname from Middle Dutch <i>hasart</i> ‘hare’."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Hebrew: Bitter; Marion is the French form."],"variants":[{"name":"Marion","meanings":["Originally a medieval French diminutive form of   Marie  , introduced to Britain in the Middle Ages. In some places it was taken as a pet form of   Margaret   or   Margery .  As a male name, it is an altered form of the Continental male name <i>Marian</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>Marianus</i> (from   Marius  ), but is now rarely, if ever, used. It was the birth name of the American film star  John Wayne  (  1907–79 )."]},{"name":"Marcia","meanings":["Often used as a feminine equivalent of   Mark  , but in fact a feminine form of <i>Marcius</i>, itself a derivative of   Marcus .  One  St Marcia  is commemorated in a group with Felix, Luciolus, Fortunatus, and others; another with Zenais, Cyria, and Valeria; and a third with Ariston, Crescentian, Eutychian, Urban, Vitalis, Justus, Felicissimus, Felix, and Symphorosa. None is individually very famous."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":29,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":60,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":85,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":98,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":107,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdicti